close_symbols: size macros used by os_dirent_t (e.g. OS_MAX_PATH_LEN, PATH_MAX)
explanation:
- os_dirent_t: The structure definition (field names and array sizes) is essential to determine whether any string writes (e.g. into d_name or similar char arrays) performed by called code can overflow the destination.
- OS_DirRead_Impl: This is the underlying implementation that actually performs the directory read and is the most likely place string.h functions (memcpy/strcpy/strncpy/strncat/strlen/etc.) are used to populate the passed dirent. Its body must be inspected for any potentially out-of-bounds string accesses.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: OS_DirRead_Impl calls this function (per the call graph). If it performs name lookups or copies, it may contain string operations that could overflow buffers; include it to follow the data flow and string usage.
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: The macro/function invoked at the start may alter control flow (return on NULL) or call diagnostics; ensure it does not perform any hidden string operations or side effects relevant to buffer safety.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Although primarily an identity/token acquisition function, its behavior determines whether OS_DirRead_Impl is called (success path) and whether any tokens or pointers passed to implementations are valid. Include to confirm it does not touch dirent or use string functions unexpectedly.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Examine to ensure no further use of the dirent buffer or unexpected string operations occur during release/cleanup.
- OS_object_token_t: Type definition of the token passed into OS_DirRead_Impl is needed to understand what the implementation expects and whether any fields inside the token influence string copying or buffer sizes.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success return value constant is required to understand the control flow (i.e. when OS_DirRead_Impl is invoked) and reason about the code paths that may perform string operations.
- size macros used by os_dirent_t (e.g. OS_MAX_PATH_LEN, PATH_MAX): Any compile-time constants that define buffer lengths inside os_dirent_t or used by the implementations are required to verify that string operations respect those bounds.

These symbols collectively allow tracing where string.h functions may be used, what destination buffers they target, and the compile-time sizes/limits needed to determine whether any string operations can access beyond object bounds.
